Principal Component Analysis (Task)

The “cities30.csv” dataset includes the rating on 30 cities in 9 dimensions. 1. Climate and Terrain (the higher the score the better) 2. Housing (the lower the score the better) 3. Health Care & the Environment (the higher the score the better) 4. Crime (the lower the score the better) 5. Transportation (the higher the score the better) 6. Education (the higher the score the better) 7. The Arts (the higher the score the better) 8. Recreation (the higher the score the better) 9. Economics (the higher the score the better)

3. Conduct PCA using the above 9 variables

c.pca <- PCA(cities_PCA,  graph = TRUE) #removed scale & column removal portions of code from practice, already completed

print(c.pca)

4. Interpret the results including the components, eigenvalues, quality of representation (cos2), the resulted map(s)

fviz_eig(c.pca, addlabels = TRUE, ylim = c(0, 35))

The bar plot shows a more dramatic visual of how much more the first two dimensions account for variance in the data than the next dimensions 3 and 4

In Dim 1, Healthcare and Arts hold the highest influence while in Dim 2, Climate and Housing hold the highest influence

library(corrplot)

This simple correlation matrix also supplements my previous findings

fviz_cos2(c.pca, choice = "var", axes = 1:2)

The Cos2 gives us a better visual as to which variables we’re looking at that influence our data, rather than their variance in terms of “dimensions”

fviz_pca_var(c.pca, col.var = "cos2",
             gradient.cols = c("blue", "yellow", "red"),
             repel = TRUE)

fviz_pca_ind(c.pca, col.ind = "cos2",

It seems to me that cities considered to be “midwestern” have arts and healthcare as bigger predictors, whereas housing and climate are bigger predictors for west coast cities with large populations

7. Use the “pop” (population) as the supplementary variable and predict its position on the map

pop.pca <- PCA(cities30[, 2:11], scale.unit = TRUE, quanti.sup = 10,  graph= TRUE)

As discussed previously, the first four dimensions account for over 75% of the variance in the data with the first two dimensions accounting for over 1/2 of the variance in the data

Arts, Healthcare, Climate and Housing should all be used in further analysis

PCA actually provided us with a segmentation of our data as well, since our first two dimensions divided between geographic location quite visibly to Midwest versus California

New York appears to be an outlier when it comes to what dimensions are causing the greatest variance in data, as it is affected so much more severely than other cities - should it be separated for its own individual analysis?

Population is predicted to account for a noticeable, but not substantial, amount of variance in the data
